To LEW and others....<br><br>
There is a commonality that I feel with others on this<br>
site. It is based on coming together and speaking<br>
the truth as we know it. I have respect for those<br>
who I disagree with, because they took the risk of<br>
speaking openly, respectfully and honestly. While I<br>
may intelectually agree with you (LEW) on some issues<br>
I feel much more respect for Cook, Edward, Tom or Art<br>
because they are working with me to find out something, to<br>
understand. As always, the issue is not what you believe,<br>
but what you do. You are being disruptive, combatative,<br>
and generaaly unpleasant. I will no longer adress you,<br>
or respond to your  posts if this continues. <br><br>
I ask all others to take the same approach.I will only<br>
respond to those who care to listen. As a general guideline,<br>
those who are disruptive should be told that they are<br>
being disruptive. If they continue and do not change their<br>
ways we will ignore them and take away their voice.<br><br>
Which brings me back to our general discussion. What I <br>
think helped to alienate the people at home, even<br>
to the point of VFW's and other Vets organizations being<br>
un-welcoming was an inability for us to understand the<br>
war because we were never told the truth. Each night we<br>
would hear the news and could tell that it was a bunch of<br>
lies. We could not support what we did not understand,<br>
and could not understand why Vets were coming home and<br>
feeling so totally alienated andd unable to reintegrate <br>
with society. By this statement I do not mean the anti-war<br>
segment of society, but I mean all of America. <br><br>
When Vets came home from WWII or Korea, the people at <br>
home understood why they went and the reasons for what <br>
they did. When Vets came back from VN we did not understand<br>
why they went or why they (you) did what you did. The<br>
resons for the war were not something we could understand. It<br>
was the fault of the government for sending troups overseas<br>
without first building the support for the actions on the<br>
part of the American people. If they had done so, the<br>
reactions to the returning Vet would have been different. If<br>
they could not get that support then they had no right to send <br>
troups in the first place. <br><br>
The American people in general, some of the anti-war <br>
movement in particular, targeted the vets as the problem<br>
and did not understand that they (you) were a part of<br>
the same confusion that effected us all. 
